They therefore say that the first advances and over-tures, and the original inclination to form an attachment, are prompted by the desire for pleasure, but that when the progr-ess of intercourse has led to intimacy, the relationship blossoms into an affection strong enough to make us love our friends for their own sake, even though no practical advantage accrues from their friendship. Does not familiarity endear to us localities‚ temples, cities, gymnasia and playing- grounds, horses and hounds, gladiatorial shows and fights with wild beasts?
